<section class="intro">
Sometimes the most important moments in teaching happen when the teacher steps back. The lesson drifts slightly off script. A student says something unexpected. The room changes.

This blog collects those moments — small narrative reflections from the strange and beautiful ecosystem of a classroom.
</section>

<section id="about" class="about">
<h2 class="section-title">About This Blog</h2>

<p>
Teachers spend much of their time at the front of the room — explaining, guiding, directing the flow of a lesson. But the most interesting teaching often happens somewhere else: slightly offstage, when students begin to take ownership of meaning.
</p>

<p>
Teaching from the Dark Side of the Room records those moments. It is a notebook of classroom stories, unexpected insights, and the quiet evidence that learning is happening in ways we never planned.
</p>

<p>
Each entry begins with a moment in the room and follows the thread of what that moment might reveal about teaching, curiosity, and the creative life of a classroom.
</p>

</section>

